## Where Businesses Often Go Wrong with Cash  
Even profitable companies can face cash flow shortfalls. Here are common missteps to watch for:

- Confusing profit with available cash. Profitability doesn‚Äôt equal liquidity if money hasn‚Äôt arrived. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}  
- Poor collections management. Unpaid invoices turn into a cash gap. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}  
- Seasonal planning failures. Basing costs on peak months leads to holes during slower periods. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}  
- Inventory mismanagement. For product businesses, excess stock ties up cash. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}  
- Over-optimistic revenue projections. Spending ahead of realised income creates pressure. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}  
- Ignoring payment term mismatches. Paying suppliers quickly while waiting weeks to collect kills cash flow. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

---

## Why Selling More Isn‚Äôt Always the Answer  
Growth feels good‚Äîbut more sales can actually **make cash flow issues worse** if underlying processes aren‚Äôt optimized. More sales often mean more complexity, more working capital tied up, and stronger exposure to operational inefficiencies. If you don‚Äôt first fix the internal financial systems, you‚Äôre just adding water to a leaky bucket. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}

